f=AGENT-BUILD-PLAYBOOK.md · h1:Agent Build Playbook=build any agent system, consistent structure standard. rule reflects something actually tested, corrected, confirmed while building first agent system theory. you're building agent assigned you, follow order. Don't skip steps, don't batch steps together even feels slow order stops point. playbook self-contained doesn't assume you access any agent's folder reference. Everything you need described directly. **Companion docs (read alongside one):** `LOGICAL-SYNTHESIS-PLAN.md` detailed process logical-grounding pass expanded §8. Supplied source books `Agents/_books/`. Cross-agent capabilities shared references live `Shared OS/` (see §13). · h2:1. Choose Scope=**1.1 Pick department.** Suggest next department build order ask person confirm (or pick different one). Don't assume previously-used order still applies without asking. **1.2 Pick agent within department.** List agents department (from org chart catalog) ask which one start with. Don't move past step until confirmed. · h2:Sort Marketplace vs. Custom=Once skill list settled, split two buckets: · h2:Sort Marketplace vs. Custom=**Marketplace** real, existing skill probably fulfill this., **Custom** needs built scratch merged multiple sources. · h2:Sort Marketplace vs. Custom=**Default marketplace first, time.** standing rule, per-agent question real, sourced skills cheaper verify faster get right something built scratch, exhaust marketplace search before starting custom work. skip straight custom skill list discussion section already made clear nothing marketplace-sourced plausibly fit. · h2:Build Custom Skills (one time)=Custom skills need involvement research. Before drafting any it, apply rule 0.1: tell person what you're planning build, (what gap fills, what it's based on), (the design/method), get sign-off before writing. finished skill define, minimum: · h2:Build Custom Skills (one time)=**Introduction** what came (built scratch, merged which sources)., **Purpose** what problem solves whom., **Structure/Protocol** phases steps runs through, shown simple flow., **Instructions** actual step-by-step method, detailed enough agent won't drift guess., **Fallback** what information missing, dependency isn't available, skill doesn't cleanly apply., **Principles** non-negotiable rules specific skill (no fabrication, escalate ties, etc. whatever applies)., **Boundaries skills** hands off depends agent's skills. · h2:Build Custom Skills (one time)=**5.1 Discuss scoring/criteria/method design explicitly.** skill involves scoring, ranking, any formula, don't invent criteria unilaterally propose design, ask expanded changed, confirm before building. **5.2 Discuss tool needs.** skill benefit external data access ("map access" i.e. data source/connector) needs Python script (for multi-step math, scoring, anything better done code reasoning), raise explicitly get agreement before building. script approved, write it, test sample input, confirm actually runs correctly before presenting skill done. **5.3 One skill, stop.** marketplace: build, present, wait review. · h2:Operational Layer What Goes Subfolder=**7.0 Prioritize before building; don't march through fixed order.** Look what specific agent's skills actually need build subfolder matters *for agent* first don't default mechanical principles→commands→agent→skill→tool march because that's order they're listed in. decision-heavy agent, principles matter first; agent whose skills barely overlap, skill-routing matter least. Ask judge which load-bearing particular agent start there. **7.0a Check whether subfolder needs real content before writing any; always keep folder itself.** agent needs real content one five subfolders. Before building any principles/commands/agent/skill/tool, check: agent's actual skill set give you real material build from? not, don't pad out content copied another agent's shape completeness still **create keep empty folder** overall folder structure stays identical predictable across agent (an agent that's missing whole subfolder harder reason about one intentionally empty one). subfolder left empty, that's decision worth one-line note (even stray `.gitkeep`-style placeholder explaining nothing's yet) rather silence. lesson `agent/` config discussion below, generalized whole operational layer: derive content, don't default don't derive folder *structure* away either. Build whichever subfolders apply one time, stop-and-review discipline everywhere else apply rule 0.1 before each: say what you're about consolidate, it's structured way, (which existing sources it's pulled from), before writing it. sourced what's *already* defined across agent's skill files don't invent new rules here, consolidate existing ones. · h2:Operational Layer What Goes Subfolder=**principles/** hard, cross-skill rules agent always follows regardless which skill running (no fabrication, escalate close calls, etc.). **Only department leader's principles file gets Universal Identity-Flavored split.** agent (not department leader) gets **Universal-only** identity-flavored section, since non-leader agents identity their (see 6.1). Don't reuse leader's identity-driven tone rules non-leader agent default; non-leader agent seems need tone guidance, that's separate discussion, inheritance., **commands/** consolidated trigger-phrase table (pulled skill's "When Use" section) mapping natural-language phrases which skill fires, plus optional slash-style shortcuts convenience layer, plus precedence rules any triggers overlap across agent's skills. **The document's structure/layout agent** (same table shape, sections) actual triggers, shortcuts, precedence rules inside unique agent's specific skill set. Don't copy another agent's trigger content, shape., **agent/** machine-readable config things skills reference shouldn't hardcode: escalation thresholds, escalation contacts/routing, model routing, tool permissions. real values aren't known yet, build explicit fill-in-later template placeholder fields never invent numbers. **Derive field list what specific agent's skills actually reference don't copy another agent's config shape.** field trace back real line one agent's skill files. agent fewer external dependencies get smaller config, padded-out copy different agent's structure empty sections nothing points to. (This 7.0a applies concretely nothing agent's skills references config value all, subfolder need building.), **skill/** agent's skill-routing map: which skill hands off which, what order, what takes precedence request match one. Sourced skill's "Boundaries skills" section. Note top identity fits leader agent (it governs *how*), explicitly note "no identity layer" non-leader agents either way, file governs *which/when*, tone., **tool/** technical requirements table: what skill actually needs function (file read/write, script execution, etc.), derived directly what's written skill files governance/policy layer (that's `agent/`'s `tool_permissions`), *technical* layer. **This file state explicitly, near top, specifies needs grant them** listing "Python/shell execution" table give agent capability. Actual tool/file/execution access separate runtime-configuration step, set wherever agent actually deployed Claude Skills-compatible platform's permission system, whatever infrastructure human operator sets run process manually). table checklist whoever configuration, functioning permission grant itself. tool/ file built carry disclaimer optional implied. · h2:Operational Layer What Goes Subfolder=**Cross-agent capabilities (like web search) any individual skill file.** skill benefit something that's really shared, cross-agent capability, don't bake locally note dependency shared OS-level skill layer separate, not-yet-built layer meant shared across agent) instead. · h2:9. agent.md=One file agent, root folder, containing: · h2:9. agent.md=**Summary** what agent does, sentences., **Purpose** specific problems solves., **Position org** department, role, who owns it, many agents department their status., **Skill roster** table folder (marketplace, custom) showing skill name, status, source/notes including anything still pending, named explicitly pending, silently omitted., **Identity/operational/logical status** what's built, what's placeholder, what's started., **Workflow** strict, detailed routing logic agent operate once fully built (which skill handles which kind request, what order, escalation points). · h2:9. agent.md=Update file agent's build progresses always reflect current reality, stale snapshot. · h2:11. Skill File Standard (applies SKILL.md, marketplace custom)=skill file needs frontmatter documenting provenance clear enough structure agent never gets confused about boundaries. Minimum frontmatter fields: Body structure custom skills: Introduction, Purpose, Use, Structure/Protocol, Instructions (phase phase), Output Format, Principles, Fallback, Boundaries Skills. Marketplace copies keep source's structure, comment block top explaining selected what catalog entry fulfills. · h2:13. Shared Global Layer=`Shared OS/` holds capabilities belong *no single agent* because agent needs them. rule thumb one line: **agent-specific lives agent's `custom/`; cross-agent lives `Shared OS/` cited, copied.** Building capability ten agents means ten copies drift fix; building once citing keeps one source truth. **13.1 Inherited, owned.** agent never copies shared capability folder. operational `skill/` routing (or relevant skill file) names dependency reference e.g. *"Shared layer (inherited, owned): verification-before-completion"* way §7's closing note already routes cross-agent capabilities like web search layer instead baking them locally. capability real; ownership central. **13.2 What lives here.** · h2:13. Shared Global Layer=**Shared skills** cross-agent capabilities: `verification-before-completion`, `web-search`, `memory-practices`, similar. Built once, cited agent needs them., **Shared scripts** script used fleet-wide lives `Shared OS/` cited many skills call it, rather duplicated each., **Shared logical scripts** highest-leverage case (see §8.7 §13.5): book used many agents extracted once Python script `Shared OS/logical/`; agents import there. scripts pure formula libraries .md reference files. Extract once, import many. · h2:13. Shared Global Layer=**13.3 agent uses it.** build time, skill benefit something that's really cross-agent, build locally (§7's rule). Instead: (a) confirm whether shared capability exists `Shared OS/` yet; (b) does, cite agent's operational `skill/` file inherited dependency; (c) doesn't yet, note dependency shared layer it's built once inherited never quietly reproduced inside agent. **13.4 build discipline.** Shared artifacts still built one time under rules 0.1/0.2 difference *where* they live they're referenced rather duplicated. change shared artifact propagates agent cites it, which whole point: fix once, fixed everywhere. **13.5 Logical scripts live Shared OS/logical/ (added 2026-07-14).** logical .py scripts `Shared OS/logical/` one flat folder, subfolders. script formula library sourced real book self-tests. rules: · h2:13. Shared Global Layer=**One flat folder, nesting.** `Shared OS/logical/` contains .py .md files. subfolders, per-agent subfolders. .md files permitted practitioner-operator wisdom extractions (§8.9) qualitative mental models extracted builder-authored books. logical artifacts .py scripts., **Agent logical/ folders minimal.** agent's `logical/` folder contains `book-requirements.md` (which records what books ground agent's judgments scripts live). .py files agent logical/ folders they import `Shared OS/logical/`., **Skills call scripts import.** agent's skill file references logical script dependency e.g., "Financial formulas: import Shared OS/logical/capital_budgeting.py." skill owns domain logic; script owns math., **Books produce scripts cited .md files.** synthesis pipeline (§8.3) produces Python scripts self-tests anything formulas (Routes A/B/C). Route (practitioner-operator wisdom, §8.9) produce cited .md file instead qualitative extracts chapter/page references. script documentation mathematical extractions inline docstrings carry book/section/page citations., **Cross-agent scripts don't get copied.** vista's roadmap-sync needs forecasting formulas, imports `Shared OS/logical/forecasting.py` get copy. rule §13.1 applied logical layer., **Shared OS/logical/ system record.** script updated (bug fix, new edition book), agent imports gets fix automatically. original intent §8.7's "extract once, cite many" enforced file level.